  "ancestors": [
    {
      "code": "pt-PT",
      "role": "superstrate",
      "weight": 0.7,
      "notes": "European Portuguese superstrate from 15th–18th century colonial contact. Primary lexifier. Phonological system largely derived from archaic PT (no /ɨ/, preservation of nasal vowels)."
    },
    {
      "code": "ff",
      "role": "substrate",
      "weight": 0.15,
      "notes": "Fula/Fulah substrate: major language group of Guinea-Bissau interior. Contributes nasal vowels and some prenasalized consonants."
    }
  ],
  "notes": "Guinea-Bissau Creole (Kriol / GBC / Guinean Creole). Portuguese-based Atlantic creole; true national lingua franca of Guinea-Bissau (~600,000 L1 speakers, ~2 million total). KEY FEATURES: (1) NASAL VOWELS: ã/ẽ/ĩ/õ/ũ phonemic, influenced by Mandinka and Fula substrates. (2) FIVE-VOWEL SYSTEM: no /ɨ/. (3) PRENASALIZED STOPS: mb/nd from Bantu and Mande substrate. (4) AFFRICATES: dj=[dʒ], tx=[tʃ]; j may also render [dʒ] (competing conventions). (5) WORD-FINAL SIMPLIFICATION: final consonants may be reduced or deleted. (6) RHOTIC: alveolar [r]. Closely related to Cape Verdean Creole (kea); both belong to the Upper Guinea Creole cluster. Not to be confused with Guinean French-based Créole (Guinée-Conakry).",
